first_dataframe <- left_join(flights,

1.3 Question 1

What is the arrival delay in the first three month of 2015? Observation: Looking into the visualization below, we can see that the highest delay (700 mins) was before March. From this, we can think about the reason why it was like that. We can come up with the new question later whether the delay time happening because of the bad weather before March.And there are a pattern before March for the delay.

d<- as.POSIXct(total_dataframe$FLIGHT_DATE, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
total_dataframe$dm <- format(d, "%m")

p <- ggplot(total_dataframe, aes(x=d, y=ARRIVAL_DELAY)) +
  geom_line(color='orange',size=1) + 
  xlab("Date")
p

1.4 Question 2

What is the density of the highest elapsed time? Observation:Looking into the visualization below, we can notice that the highest elapsed time was around 60-80 minutes or 120-140 minutes at the density around 0.009 - 0.0100. From this, we can relate to the real situation in real life, most of the time, flights get delayed around 1-2 hours. This can be one of the reasons for that.

np <- ggplot(data=total_dataframe,aes(x=ELAPSED_TIME, xlab = 'elapsed time')) +
  geom_density(color = "orange",fill="black",alpha=0.6,size=1,adjust=1) + 
  ggtitle("Density of elapsed time")
np

1.5 Question 3

What is the median distance travel of each airlines ? Compare the highest median with the lowest median? Observation:In the visualization below, we can see that the higest median distance is from F9(Frontier Airlines Inc.) airline, and the lowest one is from OO(Skywest Airlines Inc.). From this, it can explain that maybe F9 is having more destinations or longer distance between location than OO throughout the United State.

ggplot(total_dataframe,aes(AIRLINE,DISTANCE,fill=AIRLINE))+
  geom_boxplot(width=0.05,fill="orange",outlier.color = NA)+
  stat_summary(fun = median,geom = "point",fill="white",size=2.5,shape=21)

2.4 Question 3

What is the density of the highest region and why? Observation:Looking into the data visualization below, it is fascinating to see that the highest density for faculty salary avg is the Midwest region and the second-highest in the South region. But the highest salary is from the West and Northeast. For the highest salary, we can explain that maybe their tuition is expensive (with above explanation) to afford to pay more for the faculty.

ggplot(data=college,aes(x=faculty_salary_avg,color=region,fill=region))+ geom_density(alpha = 0.2,size=1,linetype="solid")+
  scale_color_manual(values =colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"))(4))+
  scale_fill_manual(values =colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(8,"Dark2"))(4))+
ggtitle("Density plot of faculty_salary_avg in different regions")
